      "target": {
        "kind": "pull_request",
        "title": "fix(auto-reply): guard optional getFailedCounts on dispatcher variants",
        "body": "Fixes #89116\n\n## Summary\n\n`getDispatcherFinalOutcomeCounts()` in `src/auto-reply/reply/dispatch-from-config.ts` called `dispatcher.getFailedCounts().final` without optional chaining, while the adjacent `getCancelledCounts?.().final ?? 0` line already guarded against the method being absent. Some `ReplyDispatcher` variants do not implement every count method, so the unguarded call threw `TypeError: dispatcher.getFailedCounts is not a function`.\n\nRoot cause: the `ReplyDispatcher` type declared `getCancelledCounts?` optional but `getFailedCounts` required, even though dispatcher variants may omit either. This PR aligns the type (`getFailedCounts?` is now optional like `getCancelledCounts?`) and guards the remaining call sites:\n\n- `dispatch-from-config.ts` — `getDispatcherFinalOutcomeCounts` now uses `getFailedCounts?.().final ?? 0`\n- `dispatch-from-config.ts` — the active-dispatch wrapper falls back to empty counts when the underlying method is absent\n- `dispatch-acp-delivery.ts` — the visible-text delivery path guards `getFailedCounts?.()`\n\n## Real behavior proof\n\n**Behavior addressed:** A `ReplyDispatcher` variant that omits `getFailedCounts` no longer crashes the final-outcome accounting path with `TypeError: dispatcher.getFailedCounts is not a function`; the failed count safely resolves to `0`, while dispatchers that do implement it keep using the real counts.\n\n**Real environment tested:** Linux x86_64, Node.js v22, HEAD `38abdc7ce5d95da1b1b4dcd612c5999c6ec7cc6d` based on `origin/main` `ab1042d11582fabf1f0740dd7d0bd156b339aba6`. Production function `getDispatcherFinalOutcomeCounts` driven directly via `node --import tsx`, plus focused Vitest unit coverage.\n\n**Exact steps or command run after this patch:**\n```\n# Drive the production function with a dispatcher variant missing getFailedCounts:\nnode --import tsx -e 'import(\"./src/auto-reply/reply/dispatch-from-config.ts\").then((m) => {\n  const partial = { getCancelledCounts: () => ({ tool: 0, block: 0, final: 2 }) };\n  let beforeErr = \"(no error)\";\n  try { partial.getFailedCounts().final; } catch (e) { beforeErr = e.constructor.name + \": \" + e.message; }\n  console.log(\"BEFORE:\", beforeErr);\n  console.log(\"AFTER :\", JSON.stringify(m.getDispatcherFinalOutcomeCounts(partial)));\n  const full = { getCancelledCounts: () => ({ tool:0, block:0, final:1 }), getFailedCounts: () => ({ tool:0, block:0, final:5 }) };\n  console.log(\"FULL  :\", JSON.stringify(m.getDispatcherFinalOutcomeCounts(full)));\n})'\n\n# Focused regression suite:\nOPENCLAW_VITEST_MAX_WORKERS=1 node scripts/run-vitest.mjs run \\\n  src/auto-reply/reply/dispatch-from-config.final-outcome-counts.test.ts --reporter=dot\n```\n\n**Evidence after fix:**\n```\nBEFORE: TypeError: partial.getFailedCounts is not a function\nAFTER : {\"cancelled\":2,\"failed\":0}\nFULL  : {\"cancelled\":1,\"failed\":5}\n\n Test Files  1 passed (1)\n      Tests  3 passed (3)\n```\n\n**Observed result after fix:** The unguarded pre-fix call reproduces the reported `TypeError`. After the patch, the production `getDispatcherFinalOutcomeCounts` returns `{cancelled: 2, failed: 0}` for the method-less dispatcher (no throw) and `{cancelled: 1, failed: 5}` for a full dispatcher. `tsgo:core` passes.\n\n**What was not tested:** End-to-end live dispatch against a real gateway run; the fix is exercised through the production accounting function with representative dispatcher variants and unit tests rather than a full live reply cycle.\n",
        "branch": "fix/89116-dispatch-failed-counts",
